Diagnosis . Thorax (except scutellum) black in ground colour; scutellum red on posterior 1 / 3 or more. Abdomen black (rarely reddish on sides of abdominal tergites 3 and 4 ), sometimes with bronze or dark blue reflections, covered with more or less dense grey or golden­grey microtrichosity (very dense with shifting spots in the specimens from Sicily). Usually 1 reclinate upper orbital seta (about 20 % of the material examined have 2 ); lateral vertical seta weak, not or slightly differentiated from the postocular setulae. ɗ: postpedicel about 2.2–3.3 times as long as pedicel; parafacial (in lateral view) at its narrowest point 0.43–0.75 times as wide as postpedicel; frons 0.83–1.3 times as wide as an eye in dorsal view; legs entirely black (rarely tibiae dark brown); claws at least as long as tarsomere 5 (fore claws longer than tarsomere 5 ); cerci short and stout; surstylus shorter than cerci in lateral view (as in
Fig. 17
). Ψ: postpedicel about 1.7–2.6 times as long as pedicel; lateral vertical setae strong, well differentiated from the postocular row; frons 0.9–1.3 times as wide as an eye in dorsal view.
